04790nam a22005775i 9780822381457DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780822381457  a(DE-B1597)554035  a(OCoLC)1055300681  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0330002bisacsh1 aBecker, Marc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIndians and Leftists in the Making of Ecuador's Modern Indigenous Movements /cMarc Becker; ed. by Sonia Saldívar-Hull, Irene Silverblatt, Walter D. Mignolo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (330 p.) :b24 b&w photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChronology -- tAcronyms -- tOne What Is an Indian? -- tTwo Socialism -- tThree Strike! -- tFour Federación Ecuatoriana de Indios -- tFive Guachalá -- tSix Agrarian Reform? -- tSeven Return of the Indian -- tEight Pachakutik -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBiographies -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn June 1990, Indigenous peoples shocked Ecuadorian elites with a powerful uprising that paralyzed the country for a week. Militants insisted that the government address Indigenous demands for land ownership, education, and economic development. This uprising was a milestone in the history of Ecuador’s social justice movements, and it inspired popular organizing efforts across Latin America. While the insurrection seemed to come out of nowhere, Marc Becker demonstrates that it emerged out of years of organizing and developing strategies to advance Indigenous rights. In this richly documented account, he chronicles a long history of Indigenous political activism in Ecuador, from the creation of the first local agricultural syndicates in the 1920s through the galvanizing protests of 1990. In so doing, he reveals the central role of women in Indigenous movements and the history of productive collaborations between rural Indigenous activists and urban leftist intellectuals.Becker explains how rural laborers and urban activists worked together in Ecuador, merging ethnic and class-based struggles for social justice. Socialists were often the first to defend Indigenous languages, cultures, and social organizations. They introduced rural activists to new tactics, including demonstrations and strikes. Drawing on leftist influences, Indigenous peoples became adept at reacting to immediate, local forms of exploitation while at the same time addressing broader underlying structural inequities. Through an examination of strike activity in the 1930s, the establishment of a national-level Ecuadorian Federation of Indians in 1944, and agitation for agrarian reform in the 1960s, Becker shows that the history of Indigenous mobilizations in Ecuador is longer and deeper than many contemporary observers have recognized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCommunismzEcuadorzCayambe. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorzCayambexPolitics and government. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorzCayambexSocial conditions. 0aSocial movementszEcuadorzCayambe. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107118370 cprintz978082234256440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822381457423Coveruhttps://w